\subsection{Distinguishing Hecke operators}
\begin{definition}\label{cmf.distinguishing_primes}
\uses{cmf.galois_orbit,cmf.hecke_operator,cmf.newform,cmf.newspace}
For a {{KNOWL('cmf.newspace', 'newspace')}} $S^\mathrm{new}_k(N,\chi)$ we say that a set of {{KNOWL('cmf.hecke_operator', 'Hecke operators')}} $\mathcal T:=\{T_{p_1},\ldots,T_{p_r}\}$ **distinguishes** the {{KNOWL('cmf.newform', 'newforms')}} in the space if the sets $X_f(\mathcal T)$ of characteristic polynomials of the $T_p\in \mathcal T$ acting on the subspace $V_f$ spanned by the {{KNOWL('cmf.galois_orbit', 'Galois orbit')}} of $f$ in $S_k^\mathrm{new}(N,\chi)$ are distinct as $f$ ranges over (non-conjugate) newforms in $S_k^\mathrm{new}(N,\chi)$.

The set $\mathcal T$ can be identified by a list of primes $p$.  For convenience we restrict to primes $p$ that do not divide the level $N$ and list the unique ordered sequence of primes $p_1,\ldots,p_n$ for which the sequence of integers $c_1,\ldots,c_n$ defined by
\[
c_m := \#\bigl\{X_f(\{T_{p_i}:i < m\}): \mathrm{newforms}\ f\in S_k^\mathrm{new}(N,\chi)\bigr\}
\]
is strictly increasing.  The length of the sequence $p_1,\ldots p_n$ is always less then the number of newforms in $S_k^\mathrm{new}(N,\chi)$ and we obtain the empty sequence when $S_k^\mathrm{new}(N,\chi)$ contains just one newform.
\end{definition}


